Part 4

After the night downstairs at the press building, Vikram stopped explaining his evenings to anyone. 

Pradhan-babu noticed that the office lights stayed on much later, the yellow glow from the corner windows shining onto the empty courtyard long after the clerks had gone home. 

Rohan noticed that his brother had stopped mentioning names of any kind, whether friends or business associates. It was the way a man stops walking near a particular street corner after he has twisted his ankle in a pothole there once.

Neither of them said anything. Work absorbed what the quiet evenings used to hold. 

By thirty, the company's Odisha operations ran themselves well enough that Pradhan-babu, who was now nearing his retirement in earnest, told anyone who asked: "Ahuja Sahib could run this entire state with his eyes closed. Which is a problem, because a man needs something to keep his eyes open for."

Nobody quite understood what the old manager meant by that, except Vikram.

---

The telephone call came on a hot Tuesday afternoon. This time, it was not from his uncle, but from the family doctor directly, using the flat, unhesitating tone doctors use only when there is nothing left to soften.

"Mr. Ahuja, I won't use words like 'let's see' this time," the doctor said. "Your father's liver has failed past the point where monitoring or hope means anything. We are looking at weeks. Possibly a few months, if he is very fortunate and very careful."

Ten years had passed since the first scare in the Shobhabazar clinic. Ten years of business lists and licenses, and this time the sentence didn't leave any doors open. 

Vikram sat with the heavy receiver still pressed against his ear long after the doctor had disconnected. The dial tone hummed in the quiet office, the particular silence of a fact that has stopped being negotiable.

---

Binay Ahuja insisted on attending the scheduled board meeting anyway, refusing to remain in his bed.

"If I am going, Vikram," he said as they rode in the back of the car, "I am going having placed you in that Chairman's chair myself. I will not leave it for the lawyers and the vultures to argue over after I am in the ground."

The boardroom held twelve men that morning. They sat around the same long teak table Vikram had once sat beside as a teenager, signing ledgers Pradhan-babu slid across to him. 

Except now, three of the twelve directors stood up slightly straighter when he entered the room, and he had stopped noticing exactly when that shift had started happening.

Binay sat at the head of the table. He was thinner than the normal frailty of ten quiet years should account for; this was a new, sharper kind of thinness that had a definite deadline attached to it. 

The agenda on the paper in front of them was simple: the South India expansion. 

It meant two new states, three major cities, a completely different tax structure, and a market that had ignored the Ahuja brand for three generations because the family had never once tried to cross the river.

Sinha, silver-haired and sharp-eyed, who had argued for Vikram's seat on this board a decade ago when the others hesitated, spoke first. "We need a younger perspective for a market like this. Someone who is unafraid of an unfamiliar map and willing to travel."

Reddy, older still, sat with his arms folded across his chest. He hadn't looked at Vikram once since the meeting began. "South India needs experience, Sinha. Not a fresh graduate's confidence."

"He has run our daily operations here for ten years," Sinha said, tapping his pen on the agenda.

"Here," Reddy said. He finally turned to face Vikram directly, his expression not unkind, but completely certain. 

"Here, where the ground was already laid by his father, and every supplier already knew the Ahuja name before Vikram even walked into the room. South India will not extend him that courtesy. Nobody down there has heard of us, and nobody down there owes us patience or trust."

He looked at Vikram properly, his eyes narrowing. "What do you know about building something that nobody is required to trust yet?"

The room went quiet, the only sound being the soft whir of the air conditioner. 

Vikram thought of a hostel corridor telephone, a pathology textbook left unopened in a friend's cupboard, and a factory supervisor twisting his cap while saying *sir* to a nineteen-year-old who didn't yet know how to sign a bank document. 

He thought of the eleven months he had spent fighting a liquor licensing policy that nobody else in this room had lost sleep over. He thought of a stone, a shattered windshield, and how nobody in this room knew about that either. 

Ten years of things that nobody in this boardroom had witnessed, and here was Reddy, entirely sincerely, asking what he knew about being unproven.

"Nothing," Vikram said finally, his voice calm. "I know nothing about it yet."

Reddy almost smiled, as if the young man's honesty confirmed his own thoughts. "Exactly my point."

"But I know what it costs to become known somewhere new," Vikram continued, looking Reddy in the eye. "I've paid that particular bill once already. I didn't enjoy it. But I would like the chance to pay it again, somewhere it might actually build something instead of just costing me my peace."

Nobody in the room understood the second sentence, and Vikram didn't bother to explain it to them.

Reddy studied him for a moment longer. "Still," he said, "it is a kid taking on a grown man's risk."

Sinha bristled. "Every leader starts somewhere, Reddy. We can't keep him in Odisha forever."

"He didn't start today," Reddy said. "That is exactly my worry. He has been quietly competent in a market that forgives him everything. I don't know yet if he is competent in a market that won't."

Binay, from the head of the table, raised one thin, trembling hand before the argument could widen between the directors.

"Meeting adjourned," Binay said. His voice cost him a great deal of effort to produce, audible in the short, raspy breath that followed it. 

"We will resume tomorrow morning, once everyone in this room remembers that we have less time than we think. Some of us considerably less than others."

The chairs scraped back against the polished floor. The twelve men filed out of the room in the particular silence of people who have been quietly, individually reminded of their own mortality by someone else's.

Vikram remained seated at the long table, looking at the empty chairs, while Reddy's question still sat in the air like smoke that hadn't found a window yet.

[End of Part 4]
